Introduction¶

Soccer performance is a multifactorial process requiring high-level interaction analysis within physiological, technical, and tactical performances. At the elite level, technical staffs need to capture, process, and analyze great amounts of data, in order to measure performance in their respective teams and opponents, as well as assess potential prospects.

Dataset Description¶

Tip: In this project , we'll be analyzing data associated with soccer matches, players, and teams from several European countries from 2008 to 2016. In particular, we'll be interested in finding the factors that detertime a league as the top league based on ther players in regard to goal types, possession, corner, cross, fouls, cards etc

The dataset contains:

  • +25,000 matches
  • +10,000 players
  • 11 European Countries with their lead championship
  • Seasons 2008 to 2016
  • Players and Teams' attributes* sourced from EA Sports' FIFA video game series, including the weekly updates
  • Team line up with squad formation (X, Y coordinates)
  • Betting odds from up to 10 providers
  • Detailed match events (goal types, possession, corner, cross, fouls, cards etc) for +10,000 matches

Dataset Link

Question(s) for Analysis¶

1. How can we measure the competitiveness of a league?

2. How many matches are there in 2016?

3. Which teams lost the fewest matches in 2016?

4. Which teams had the most wins matches in 2016?

5. Which leagues had the most matches end as a draw in 2016?

6. How many goals are there in eah league in 2016?

7. Which teams had the most wins in 2016?

8. Whuch team improvements were made over 2010-2016?

9. What's the highest player overall rating?

10. Which attributes contribute to the player's overall rating?

11. Which team attributes lead to the most wins?

Research Question 1¶

How can we measure the competitiveness of a league?¶

A first approach is the total number of goals scored in the season, if we have high number that can mean a high number of attacks in the games.

In [77]:
leagues_by_season = pd.read_sql("""SELECT Country.name AS country_name, 
                                        League.name AS league_name, 
                                        season,
                                        count(distinct stage) AS number_of_stages,
                                        count(distinct HT.team_long_name) AS number_of_teams,
                                        avg(home_team_goal) AS avg_home_team_scores, 
                                        avg(away_team_goal) AS avg_away_team_goals, 
                                        avg(home_team_goal-away_team_goal) AS avg_goal_dif, 
                                        avg(home_team_goal+away_team_goal) AS avg_goals, 
                                        sum(home_team_goal+away_team_goal) AS total_goals                                       
                                FROM Match
                                JOIN Country on Country.id = Match.country_id
                                JOIN League on League.id = Match.league_id
                                LEFT JOIN Team AS HT on HT.team_api_id = Match.home_team_api_id
                                LEFT JOIN Team AS AT on AT.team_api_id = Match.away_team_api_id
                                WHERE country_name in ('Belgium', 'England', 'France', 'Germany', 'Italy', 'Netherlands', 'Poland', 'Portugal', 'Scotland', 'Spain', 'Switzerland')
                                GROUP BY Country.name, League.name, season
                                HAVING count(distinct stage) > 10
                                ORDER BY Country.name, League.name, season
                                ;""", connection)

Research Question 2¶

How many matches are there in the 2016 season?

Create a function that returns name of winner team from every match

In [80]:
def win(match):
    """
    Input: DataFrame contains 4 columns: 
                                        `home_team_goal`, 
                                        `away_team_goal`, 
                                        `home_team_name`, 
                                        `away_team_name`
    OutPut: New Column for winner teams
    """
    home_score=match[0] #home_team_goal
    away_score=match[1] #away_team_goal
    home_team_name=match[2] #home_team_name
    away_team_name=match[3] #away_team_name
    
    if home_score > away_score:
        return home_team_name
    elif home_score < away_score:
        return away_team_name
    else:
        return 'DRAW'

Conclusions¶

Data Limitation¶

The data is collected from year 2008 till 2016

The data is only collected from some of the european teams not all of them

The dates the data was taken on are not the same for all the teams for the 8 years form 2008 to 2016, some had records for 3 or 4 years and some had more

The dataset contained match data for some teams but there were no team attributes data collected for those teams in the same season so we weren't able to use some of the match data and we had to remove those records

Analysis conclusions¶

After analyzing the data looking into the impact of playing at home on the winning percentage we can see a clear correlation between playing at home and win percentage.

We also see a correlation between buildUpPlayPositioningClass and win percentage. However there's a strong limitation on the data for this parameter as their's only 70 record for the free form vs the organized so the results can not be trusted due to the small sample size of the free form build up play positioning class

We were unable to find any relationship between defence aggression and winning percentage

We weren't able to find a relationship between build up play speed and winning percentage

Analysis of the research questions¶

Research Question 1: How can we measure the competitiveness of a league? La Liga and the Premier League beat the Bundesliga and Serie A in this field with the highest total goals scored in each of the eight seasons.

Although all the goals in one game can be score by only one team so this measure isnt really telling the degree of competitivity.

A more precise view could be the averege goal difference per match, this capture a more realistic difference between the teams, if it is low the game was even

Research Question 2: How many matches are there in the 2016 season? The top 4 teams are La Liga, Serie A, France League 1 and lastly the English Premier League with 350+ matches. Switzerland Super League had < 200 matches which consitituted to the team with the least matches in the year 2015/2016.
